The Eulerian number ⟨n, k⟩ can be computed using the formula: \[ \langle n, k \rangle = \sum_{i=0}^{k} (-1)^i \binom{n+1}{i} (k+1-i)^n \] For \( n = 13 \) and \( k = 2 \): \[ \langle 13, 2 \rangle = \sum_{i=0}^{2} (-1)^i \binom{14}{i} (3 - i)^{13} \] Calculating each term: - For \( i = 0 \): \[ (-1)^0 \binom{14}{0} \cdot 3^{13} = 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1594323 = 1594323 \] - For \( i = 1 \): \[ (-1)^1 \binom{14}{1} \cdot 2^{13} = -1 \cdot 14 \cdot 8192 = -114688 \] - For \( i = 2 \): \[ (-1)^2 \binom{14}{2} \cdot 1^{13} = 1 \cdot 91 \cdot 1 = 91 \] Summing these terms: \[ 1594323 - 114688 + 91 = 1479726 \] Thus, the number of permutations of 13 elements that can be picked up in exactly two passes is \(\boxed{1479726}\).
